<div class="aaw-about-shell" data-aaw-about>
  <section class="aaw-about-hero" aria-labelledby="aaw-about-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap aaw-about-hero-grid">
      <div class="aaw-about-hero-copy">
        <p class="aaw-about-kicker">Singapore IEM specialist</p>
        <h1 id="aaw-about-title"><span>Advanced</span><span>AcousticWerkes</span></h1>
        <p class="aaw-about-slogan">Those who listen will find the way.<span>善听者，终能找到道路。</span></p>
        <p class="aaw-about-dek">AAW is a Singapore-based in-ear monitor specialist founded in 2014 by Kevin Wang, growing out of a late-2013 R&D effort by a small team of NTU-trained engineers, makers, and music lovers.</p>
        <div class="aaw-about-actions" aria-label="About page links">
          <a class="aaw-about-btn" href="#aaw-brand-timeline">Explore timeline</a>
          <a class="aaw-about-btn secondary" href="{{ routes.all_products_collection_url }}">View monitors</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <figure class="aaw-about-hero-media">
        <img src="{{ '591A6941.jpg' | file_img_url: '1600x' }}" alt="AAW custom in-ear monitor shell work and acoustic craft" width="1600" height="2000" loading="eager">
        <figcaption>
          <b>Mechanics of Sound</b>
          <span>Listening as method, engineering as language.</span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <aside class="aaw-about-stat-strip" aria-label="AAW brand summary">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap aaw-about-stats">
      <article><b>2014</b><span>Founded in Singapore by Kevin Wang.</span></article>
      <article><b>NTU roots</b><span>Grew from a late-2013 engineering-led R&D effort.</span></article>
      <article><b>Custom + universal</b><span>Built for musicians, engineers, audiophiles, and everyday listeners.</span></article>
      <article><b>Z Series</b><span>Compact universal platforms for modern daily listening.</span></article>
    </div>
  </aside>

  <section class="aaw-about-section aaw-about-origin" aria-labelledby="aaw-origin-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap aaw-about-grid-2">
      <div>
        <p class="aaw-about-kicker">Origin</p>
        <h2 id="aaw-origin-title">Built by people who listen before they decide</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="aaw-about-copy-stack">
        <p>From the beginning, AAW was built around a simple belief: great sound is not found by force, but by listening closely - to music, to materials, to measurements, and to the people who rely on their monitors every day.</p>
        <p>AAW's early work focused on custom in-ear monitors for musicians, audio professionals, and serious listeners. Instead of treating IEM design as an assembly exercise, the team approached it as a complete acoustic system.</p>
        <p>Driver behavior, crossover architecture, shell geometry, pressure control, materials, ergonomics, and long-session comfort all had to work together. This engineering-led mindset became the foundation of AAW's identity: <strong>the Mechanics of Sound</strong>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="aaw-about-section dark aaw-about-method" aria-labelledby="aaw-method-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap">
      <div class="aaw-about-method-head">
        <div>
          <p class="aaw-about-kicker">Method</p>
          <h2 id="aaw-method-title">Sound is engineered by listening</h2>
        </div>
        <p>AAW's technology story is not a straight line of more drivers. It is a search for better ways to connect acoustic behavior, fit, and musical feeling.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="aaw-about-method-grid" aria-label="AAW engineering disciplines">
        <article><span>01</span><h3>Acoustic system design</h3><p>Driver selection, crossover behavior, chamber geometry, and pressure management are treated as one connected system.</p></article>
        <article><span>02</span><h3>Digital shell craft</h3><p>3D scanning, CAD-based acoustic development, digital modeling, and 3D printing support repeatable fit and sound.</p></article>
        <article><span>03</span><h3>Human fit data</h3><p>Universal shells are shaped by fit databases, user testing, and long-session comfort studies, not just visual proportions.</p></article>
        <article><span>04</span><h3>Hand finishing</h3><p>The final object still carries human judgment: surface finish, polish, assembly checks, and listening verification.</p></article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="aaw-brand-timeline" class="aaw-about-section aaw-about-timeline-section" aria-labelledby="aaw-timeline-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap">
      <div class="aaw-about-timeline-head">
        <div>
          <p class="aaw-about-kicker">Brand timeline</p>
          <h2 id="aaw-timeline-title">A technical evolution, not a fixed formula</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Custom IEMs led to hybrid architecture, in-house dynamic work, tunable systems, universal monitors, electrostatic and planar experiments, isobaric collaborations, modular fit, and today's Z Series platform.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="aaw-timeline-vertical" data-aaw-timeline>
        <div class="aaw-timeline-rail" aria-hidden="true"><i></i></div>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2014</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Founded in Singapore</p>
            <h3>AAW begins as an engineering-led monitor workshop</h3>
            <p>Advanced AcousticWerkes was founded in Singapore in 2014 by Kevin Wang, following a late-2013 R&D effort by a small engineering-led team with roots in NTU.</p>
            <ul><li>Serious custom IEM design</li><li>Musicians, professionals, discerning listeners</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2014</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Early hybrid custom IEMs</p>
            <h3>Hybrid design becomes part of the language</h3>
            <p>Early custom monitors such as W300AR and W500 AHMorph helped establish AAW's hybrid direction, including tunable sound concepts.</p>
            <ul><li>Dynamic-driver weight</li><li>Balanced-armature clarity</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2015</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Custom identity and early universal hints</p>
            <h3>The public record shows CIEM craft becoming visual language</h3>
            <p>AAW's Instagram archive begins in September 2015 with CIEM design work, custom faceplate storytelling, and A3H Pro builds. By December 2015, AAW was publicly teasing Nebula One as a coming universal dynamic-driver product.</p>
            <ul><li>CIEM design archive begins</li><li>A3H Pro custom work</li><li>Nebula One teased</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2016</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Universal IEM expansion</p>
            <h3>AAW tuning moves beyond custom fit</h3>
            <p>Nebula One, Nebula Two, and Q brought AAW's acoustic thinking from custom-fit monitors into smaller, more accessible universal formats. Social posts from this period also show W300AR builds, gradient shell experiments, and the Capri balanced Lightning audio cable project.</p>
            <ul><li>Nebula line enters universal fit</li><li>W300AR and shell craft continue</li><li>Capri digital cable project</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2017</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Flagship hybrid architecture</p>
            <h3>W900 pushes the high-end CIEM platform</h3>
            <p>W900 represented AAW's flagship hybrid custom monitor period, using proprietary dynamic driver work, balanced-armature arrays, and complex crossover design. AAW's own posts positioned W900 as a new flagship at CanJam Singapore 2017 and later showed W900 universal-fit builds.</p>
            <ul><li>CanJam Singapore 2017 flagship signal</li><li>High-end CIEM architecture matures</li><li>Universal-fit W900 work</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2018</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Electrostatic, universal, and planar experiments</p>
            <h3>The workshop widens its transducer vocabulary</h3>
            <p>Instagram posts from 2018 show A1D, A2H, A3H, and W900 CIEM/UIEM models at CanJam Singapore, POLA electrostatic hybrid auditions, A3H/A2H universal availability, and an advanced compact planar magnetic IEM prototype auditioned at Jaben Singapore.</p>
            <ul><li>POLA electrostatic hybrid</li><li>A1D/A2H/A3H/W900 at CanJam</li><li>Planar prototype at Jaben</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2019</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Tri-hybrid and experimental platforms</p>
            <h3>New transducer combinations enter the workshop</h3>
            <p>Canary, POLA, Nightingale, Mockingbird, ASH, AXH, and A3H appeared together in AAW's 2019 social archive through public audition activity with Zeppelin & Co. Canary was framed around construction and acoustic engineering, while Nightingale carried the planar direction forward.</p>
            <ul><li>Canary public audition era</li><li>Nightingale planar magnetic IEM</li><li>POLA, Mockingbird, ASH, AXH, and A3H</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2020</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Halcyon and tri-hybrid refinement</p>
            <h3>AAW brings electrostatic architecture into a new flagship voice</h3>
            <p>In June 2020, AAW introduced Halcyon through its social feed as a tri-hybrid driver architecture with quad electrostatic transducers, a gen-2 transformer, and a proprietary graphene-diaphragm dynamic woofer.</p>
            <ul><li>Quad electrostatic transducers</li><li>Gen-2 transformer</li><li>Graphene dynamic woofer</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2021</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Collaboration and isobaric development</p>
            <h3>AAW experiments beyond its own product line</h3>
            <p>AAW x Custom Art Project 4+2 reflected a willingness to collaborate beyond internal product lines, including isobaric dynamic woofer ideas and hybrid driver integration.</p>
            <ul><li>Cross-brand engineering collaboration</li><li>Isobaric low-frequency work enters the story</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2020s</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Universal, custom, and flagship continuity</p>
            <h3>The catalogue keeps both discipline and range</h3>
            <p>AAW continued building custom and universal models across A3H+, AXH, ATH, ASH, M20, Mockingbird, Halcyon, Nightingale, Project 4+2, and Canary Pro. Instagram adds useful detail: A3H+ Lux used the e-BFC tuning system in 2022, and the CIEM configurator gained more than 20 new designs in 2023.</p>
            <ul><li>Custom and universal families continue side by side</li><li>A3H+ Lux e-BFC tuning</li><li>CIEM configurator expansion</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2025</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Show-floor feedback and Z07 prototype work</p>
            <h3>Z07 moves from prototype listening to public demos</h3>
            <p>AAW's public Instagram posts show the Z07 prototype gathering feedback at the SIAS show in August 2025, followed by Black Malus and the new Z07 appearing at Tokyo Potafes in December 2025.</p>
            <ul><li>SIAS prototype feedback</li><li>Tokyo Potafes public showcase</li><li>Black Malus and new Z07</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>2026</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Z07 architecture becomes public</p>
            <h3>Tubeless hybrid design, adaptive fit, and 7-driver precision</h3>
            <p>In 2026, AAW's Instagram feed framed Z07 as a tube-free, filter-free hybrid IEM with a 10mm titanium dynamic driver, six balanced armatures, a 4-way electronic crossover, mechanical sound radiation, and FitMorph adaptive fit.</p>
            <ul><li>Tube-free and filter-free construction</li><li>10mm titanium DD plus 6 BA</li><li>FitMorph adaptive fit</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>CIEM</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Craft, personalization, and visible identity</p>
            <h3>Custom work remains central to the brand story</h3>
            <p>Recent social posts continue to emphasize custom Z06 and CIEM builds: resin faceplates, abalone inlays, kanji engraving, translucent shells, personal motifs, and the idea that AAW monitors should carry both acoustic intent and visual presence.</p>
            <ul><li>Z06 custom builds</li><li>Hand-finished visual identity</li><li>For those who listen beyond the surface</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="aaw-timeline-item">
          <div class="aaw-timeline-marker"><span>Z Series</span></div>
          <div class="aaw-timeline-card">
            <p class="aaw-timeline-era">Daily listening, modular fit, adaptive voicing</p>
            <h3>Z Series turns the lineage into compact daily monitors</h3>
            <p>Z06 brings Bass-Flow pressure control and digitally developed acoustic chambers. Z07 introduces FitMorph modular fit. Z05 AuAg adds TwinCore two-mode voicing, Bass-Flow venting, and a source-ready cable kit.</p>
            <ul><li>Compact universal platforms</li><li>Modern listening across phones, dongles, DAPs, and desktop systems</li></ul>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="aaw-about-section dark aaw-about-lineage" aria-labelledby="aaw-lineage-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap aaw-about-lineage-grid">
      <div>
        <p class="aaw-about-kicker">Lineage</p>
        <h2 id="aaw-lineage-title">From custom monitors to the Z Series</h2>
        <p class="aaw-about-lineage-lead">The modern catalogue reflects a balance between craft and technology: custom-fit precision, universal convenience, experimental driver systems, and products tuned for how people actually listen today.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="aaw-about-lineage-list">
        <article><span>Hybrid roots</span><p>W300AR and W500 AHMorph helped establish AAW's early hybrid direction, including tunable sound concepts.</p></article>
        <article><span>Universal growth</span><p>Nebula, Q, and later universal platforms brought AAW tuning into smaller daily listening formats.</p></article>
        <article><span>Experimental platforms</span><p>Canary, Halcyon, Nightingale, Project 4+2, and Canary Pro pushed electrostatic, planar, isobaric, and multi-way hybrid ideas.</p></article>
        <article><span>Z Series</span><p>Z06, Z07, and Z05 AuAg translate AAW's engineering language into compact universal monitors with fit, pressure, and voicing systems.</p></article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="aaw-about-section aaw-about-gallery" aria-labelledby="aaw-gallery-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap">
      <div class="aaw-about-gallery-head">
        <p class="aaw-about-kicker">Craft signals</p>
        <h2 id="aaw-gallery-title">The work lives where fit, tuning, and finish meet</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="aaw-about-gallery-grid">
        <figure class="feature">
          <img src="{{ 'builder.png' | file_img_url: '1600x' }}" alt="AAW custom builder artwork and shell design workflow" width="1600" height="1200" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption><b>Custom thinking</b><span>Personal fit and acoustic intent meet before a monitor becomes an object.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img src="{{ 'shell_CT_CQ.jpg' | file_img_url: '1200x' }}" alt="AAW custom shell and faceplate craft detail" width="1200" height="900" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption><b>Shell geometry</b><span>Comfort is part of the acoustic system.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img src="{{ 'CanaryProCIEMWeb02.jpg' | file_img_url: '1200x' }}" alt="AAW Canary Pro custom monitor product detail" width="1200" height="900" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption><b>Flagship continuity</b><span>Experimental platforms feed the next generation of practical monitors.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="aaw-about-final" aria-labelledby="aaw-final-title">
    <div class="aaw-about-wrap">
      <h2 id="aaw-final-title">Listening is not only the final test. It is the method.</h2>
      <p>It is how a shell shape is refined, how a crossover is voiced, how a stage monitor becomes dependable, and how a personal IEM becomes something a listener reaches for every day.</p>
      <p class="aaw-about-final-slogan">Those who listen will find the way.<span>We are the Mechanics of Sound.</span></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

